text:
Psychological profile: The participant reports elevated depressive symptoms (CES-D = 22, Z = 0.9), which is a salient signal relative to the study population and is one of the survey measures most strongly correlated with PSQI in this dataset (r = 0.49). Trait anxiety is not elevated (STAI = 39, Z = -0.23), and self-esteem is at the scale maximum (RSES = 40, Z = 0.26), suggesting a mixed psychological picture in which depressive symptom frequency is higher than average but global trait anxiety and self-worth are not. Subjective well-being items (e.g., current happiness Z = -0.53) are modestly below average, while health satisfaction is above average (Z = 0.55). These patterns indicate notable affective symptoms that can influence perceived sleep quality and daytime functioning even in the context of otherwise positive self-evaluations.

Behavioral and lifestyle factors: The participant reports minimal substance use and no daytime napping, but also very low frequency of exercise (exercised alone 1–2×/month; exercised with others and sports “not at all”) and extensive sedentary leisure time (sedentary hobby >4 hours, Z = 3.19; TV/videos 2–3 hours, Z = 1.91). High evening/ leisure screen and media exposure are likely (internet, listening to music each 2–3 hours; watching TV high). These behavioral features—low physical activity and high sedentary/evening media engagement—are plausibly linked to rhythm irregularity and sleep timing, and are consistent with known behavioral contributors to poorer sleep consolidation and subjective sleep complaints.

Wearable-derived physiology and circadian metrics: The participant’s heart-rate profile shows elevated baseline cardiovascular activation relative to peers (Resting HR = 78.4 bpm, Z = 2.41; Mesor = 88.34, Z = 1.97). Amplitude of the circadian heart-rate rhythm is reduced (Amplitude Z = -0.91) while interdaily stability is near average (Z = 0.17) and intradaily variability is higher than typical (Z = 1.16). The hourly aggregated deviations show the expected nocturnal reductions in heart rate (largest negative deviations between ~2–7 AM), but because the mesor and resting HR are high and amplitude is blunted, the physiological day–night contrast is attenuated. Together these features indicate elevated tonic physiological arousal and a less robust circadian amplitude, with some fragmentation of activity across the day—patterns that are commonly associated with poorer sleep quality and increased sleep complaints.

Objective sleep timing and variability: Fitbit-derived sleep shows a long median nightly duration (8 h 26 min, Z = 1.55) and a late typical sleep start (median start ≈ 01:00). Critically, sleep is highly variable across nights: sleep duration SD ≈ 193 minutes (Z = 2.09) and sleep start time SD ≈ 157 minutes (Z = 1.63). These elevated variability indicators—large night-to-night fluctuations in both duration and timing—are behaviorally important and correlate positively with PSQI in this dataset (duration SD r ≈ 0.19; start-time SD r ≈ 0.17). The pattern of relatively long average sleep duration combined with late and irregular timing suggests either inconsistent schedules (e.g., delayed/shifted sleep on some nights with compensatory long sleep on others) or frequent sleep extension, both of which can degrade subjective sleep quality and daytime functioning despite high mean duration.

Integrated interpretation and PSQI ranking: Synthesizing self-report, behavioral, and wearable data, the most salient indicators pointing toward poorer sleep quality are: elevated depressive symptoms with a strong correlation to PSQI, markedly elevated night-to-night variability in sleep timing and duration (high Z-scores), elevated resting heart rate and reduced circadian amplitude (suggesting higher physiological arousal and blunted day–night differentiation), and behavioral patterns of low physical activity and high sedentary/evening media use. The single features that might argue against poor sleep are long median sleep duration and absence of naps; however, the very high variability in timing and duration combined with psychological and physiological markers that are linked to worse PSQI make it more likely that the participant experiences subjective sleep difficulties. On balance, the evidence supports the participant having a PSQI score in the worse half of the study distribution.

Sleep timing and duration
The wearable sleep statistics indicate that this participant typically obtains a relatively long nightly sleep bout (median 7 h 49 min; Z = 0.79), but the timing of that sleep is markedly delayed and variable. The median sleep start time is very late (around 03:48), and the standard deviation of sleep duration is high (174 minutes; Z = 1.66), indicating large night-to-night variability in total sleep time. Sleep start time also shows moderate variability (SD ≈ 94 minutes; Z = 0.25). The participant reports some daytime napping (mean daily naps 0.22; Z = 1.75), suggesting occasional compensation for nocturnal timing or sleep loss. Taken together, these features describe a schedule in which sleep is often consolidated but shifted late into the morning and inconsistently timed across days, a pattern that increases the likelihood of subjective sleep complaints even when average duration appears adequate.

Physiological and circadian profile
Cardiovascular measures show a low overall mesor and low resting heart rate (Mesor = 63 bpm, Z = -1.49; Resting HR = 48.8 bpm, Z = -1.11), consistent with relatively high cardiovascular fitness or low baseline arousal. Circadian regularity metrics, however, suggest reduced day-to-day rhythm stability and greater fragmentation: interdaily stability is mildly low (0.38; Z = -0.24) while intradaily variability is modestly elevated (0.59; Z = 0.32). Hourly aggregated heart-rate deviations relative to the mesor show elevated values in late evening and around midnight–early morning (notably large positive deviations at 12–3am, with particularly high Z-scores at 1–3am), followed by strong negative deviations across the typical morning hours (4–11am). The cosinor acrophase occurs in the evening (≈ 8:48 PM), and amplitude is near the cohort mean. This pattern is consistent with a shifted activity/arousal profile in which the participant’s physiological activity remains elevated in late evening and early night, then declines markedly during the late morning—aligning with the observed late sleep onset and later wake time. The combination of reduced interdaily stability and elevated intradaily variability indicates less consistent daily structure, which commonly relates to subjective sleep disturbances.

Psychological traits and behaviors relevant to sleep
Self-report measures indicate modest elevations in trait anxiety (STAI = 45; Z = 0.37) and subthreshold depressive symptom frequency (CES-D = 15; Z = 0.18), though clinical classifications provided label the CES-D score as not depressed. Self-esteem and momentary happiness are above average (self-esteem Z = 0.82; happiness Z = 0.55), while health satisfaction is lower than average (Z = -0.78). Lifestyle behaviors include weekly alcohol use (beer and wine/liquor 1–2 times per week; Z ≈ 1.0) and relatively infrequent structured exercise. Several of these psychosocial variables (trait anxiety, depressive symptoms, low health satisfaction) have nontrivial positive correlations with PSQI in the study sample, indicating that when they are elevated they tend to co-occur with poorer subjective sleep quality. The participant’s moderate anxiety, occasional alcohol use in the evening, and low health satisfaction are therefore consistent with potential contributors to worse perceived sleep.

Integration and implications for sleep quality
Putting the multimodal evidence together: objective sleep duration is generally adequate, but the very late and irregular sleep schedule, elevated night-time cardiovascular deviations around midnight–early morning, reduced circadian stability, and modest elevations in trait anxiety/affective symptoms collectively point toward disrupted sleep organization and pre-sleep or late-evening physiological arousal. These features—particularly irregular timing and pre-sleep arousal—are well-established contributors to poorer subjective sleep quality and higher PSQI scores, even when total sleep time is not reduced. Protective indicators (long median sleep, low resting HR, higher-than-average self-esteem and happiness) moderate risk somewhat, but they do not fully offset the pattern of irregular timing and physiological arousal. Correlations in the study sample between depressive symptoms, anxiety, and PSQI further support the likelihood that the participant’s psychological profile and irregular behavior are associated with worse subjective sleep.

Overall PSQI group assessment
Considering the balance of evidence—late and inconsistent sleep timing, physiological signs of evening/early-night arousal, reduced circadian regularity, and modest anxiety/affective symptoms—I judge that this participant is more likely to fall in the higher half of PSQI scores (i.e., worse sleep quality) relative to the study population distribution.

Psychological and self-report profile: The participant’s self-report measures consistently indicate low affective burden and favorable psychosocial functioning. Depressive symptomatology on the CES-D is at the floor (score = 0; Z = -1.38) and trait anxiety is low (STAI = 24; Z = -1.71). Self-esteem and momentary happiness are elevated (RSES Z = 1.66; happiness Z = 1.64) and perceived stress is below the sample mean (Z = -0.71). Health satisfaction is above average, and reports of substance use are uniformly minimal. These survey indicators typically associate with lower subjective sleep complaints and reduced likelihood of the cognitive–emotional processes (rumination, worry) that commonly worsen self-reported sleep quality.

Wearable-derived circadian and cardiovascular signals: Heart-rate–based circadian measures point to a well-defined daily rhythm and generally low physiological arousal at rest. The participant’s resting heart rate is low (48.2 bpm; Z = -1.18) and cosinor amplitude is near average with an acrophase around early afternoon (1:01 PM), consistent with a normative daytime peak. Aggregated hourly deviations show a pronounced nocturnal dip in heart rate (large negative deviations from mesor between ~12–4 AM) and a strong morning rise (notable positive deviations 5–8 AM); these patterns indicate consolidated nocturnal quiescence and a clear circadian transition into daytime activity. Nonparametric rhythm metrics are not extreme: intradaily variability is below average (Z = -0.74), suggesting relatively low fragmentation of the heart rate signal across the day, while interdaily stability is around the sample mean (Z = -0.16), indicating only modest day-to-day regularity differences compared with peers.

Objective sleep behaviors from the wearable: The Fitbit-derived sleep summary shows a median nightly sleep duration of approximately 6 hours 11 minutes (Z = -1.25), indicating shorter sleep than the study average. Night-to-night variability in duration is substantial (SD ≈ 105 minutes), and sleep start times cluster around 23:35 with moderate variability (SD ≈ 67 minutes). Napping is absent. In sum, the dominant objective concern is reduced total sleep time coupled with appreciable variability across nights; sleep timing is moderately late but within a common student schedule.

Synthesis and implication for sleep quality (PSQI): The combined evidence presents a mixed but overall favorable profile for perceived sleep quality. Psychologically, factors that most strongly predict self-reported sleep problems (depressive symptoms and anxiety) are minimal in this participant, and high self-esteem and happiness further bias toward better subjective sleep. Physiologically, the device-derived signals (pronounced nocturnal heart-rate decline, low intradaily variability, low resting HR) are consistent with consolidated and restorative nocturnal physiology. Counterbalancing these positives is objectively short median sleep duration (~6.2 hours) and elevated night-to-night variability in sleep length; both can contribute to poorer sleep-related functioning and subjective complaints captured by PSQI domains (duration, daytime dysfunction). Given the relative strengths of the psychological and physiological indicators (which have strong links to subjective sleep quality in this dataset) and the fact that the primary objective deficit is shorter sleep—rather than fragmented nocturnal physiology or substantial circadian disruption—I judge the overall pattern to be more consistent with average-to-good sleep quality in this sample rather than markedly poor sleep.

Psychological and self-report profile: The participant reports elevated affective symptoms. Depressive symptom burden on the CES-D is 22 (Z = 0.9) and the trait anxiety score (STAI) is 62 (Z = 2.05), both of which are positively correlated with poorer PSQI in this sample (CES-D r = 0.49; STAI r = 0.40). Self-esteem is relatively low (RSES = 30, Z = -1.15, r = -0.35) and momentary happiness is low (score = 2.0, Z = -1.61), while perceived stress is modestly elevated (score = 24, Z = 0.65). These convergent self-report indicators point toward higher internalizing symptoms and lower subjective well-being, which in this dataset are associated with worse sleep quality.

Sleep timing and behavior (wearable + self-report): Wearable-derived sleep summaries show a median nightly sleep duration of 6 hours 40 minutes (Z = -0.64), which is slightly below the study average but not extremely so. Night-to-night variability in sleep timing is prominent: median sleep start is late (about 01:56) with a large standard deviation of sleep start times (SD = 215 minutes, Z = 2.89), indicating frequent large shifts in when sleep begins. Nightly sleep duration variability is also elevated (SD = 115 minutes, Z = 0.32). Napping is negligible (mean daily naps 0.08). The combination of late average sleep onset and large variability in sleep timing is a behavioral pattern commonly linked to subjective sleep disturbance and circadian misalignment, and the sleep timing variability shows a modest positive correlation with PSQI (r = 0.18).

Circadian and physiological profile from wearable data: Heart rate–based circadian metrics indicate a relatively blunted and irregular rhythm. Interdaily stability is low (0.16, Z = -2.06), and cosinor amplitude is reduced (4.2, Z = -2.13), both suggesting weak day-to-day regularity and a low-amplitude circadian signal in heart rate. Mesor is somewhat elevated (81.8 bpm, Z = 1.07) and resting heart rate is higher than average (68.2 bpm, Z = 1.2), patterns that can reflect higher physiological arousal or lower cardiovascular fitness; resting heart rate shows a small positive correlation with PSQI (r = 0.12). Hourly aggregate deviations from the mesor show modestly elevated heart rate late at night/around midnight (e.g., 12–1am +5.9 bpm, 1–2am +3.8 bpm) and pronounced negative deviations overnight (e.g., 4–7am down 11–14 bpm), consistent with periods of nocturnal reduction in rate but with some nocturnal elevation around sleep onset. Overall these circadian and heart rate features indicate a low-amplitude, poorly stabilized rhythm with modest signs of elevated nocturnal arousal and higher baseline cardiovascular tone.

Integration and inference about sleep quality: Several convergent signals point toward relatively poorer sleep quality. The strongest indicators are elevated anxiety and depressive symptoms (STAI and CES-D), late and highly variable sleep timing (median start ≈ 01:56, sleep-start SD Z = 2.89), and markedly reduced interdaily stability and amplitude of circadian heart-rate rhythms (Zs ≈ -2.1). These features have known associations with worse subjective sleep and show positive correlations with PSQI in this sample (notably CES-D r = 0.49, STAI r = 0.40). Some metrics are only mildly adverse (median sleep duration slightly below average, little napping, moderate duration variability), and the participant does not report heavy recreational drug use; however, the combination of affective symptoms and clear circadian irregularity weighs toward poorer global sleep quality. On balance, the multimodal evidence supports that this participant is more likely to fall in the upper half of the PSQI distribution (worse sleep quality).

Objective wearable-derived metrics indicate generally preserved sleep quantity and reasonably stable circadian physiology across the recording period. Median nightly sleep duration was 7 hours 32 minutes (z = 0.43), with relatively low night-to-night variability in duration (SD = 82 minutes, z = -0.43) and virtually no daytime napping (mean daily naps = 0, z = -0.86). Heart-rate–based circadian features show a robust diurnal pattern (amplitude z = 0.73) and modestly elevated interdaily stability (0.47, z = 0.50) alongside low intradaily fragmentation (intradaily variability z = -0.53). Hourly aggregate heart-rate deviations are strongly negative overnight (largest reductions between ~2–4 AM) and show pronounced daytime elevations (largest deviations mid-afternoon and early evening), consistent with consolidated nocturnal rest and distinct daytime activity periods. Taken together, these wearable indicators point to adequate objective sleep duration, consolidated nighttime physiology, and a reasonably structured rest–activity rhythm.

Self-report and behavioral measures identify several factors that could shape subjective sleep experience. The participant reports a late typical sleep start time (median ~1:15 AM) with above-average variability in sleep onset timing (start-time SD z = 0.83), substantive weekly alcohol consumption of liquor/wine (1–2 times per week; z = 0.94), and moderate evening screen/media use (watching TV/videos 1–2 hours; internet use 2–3 hours). Psychological trait scores show elevated trait anxiety (STAI = 50, z = 0.86) and higher perceived stress (score z = 0.65), while depressive symptoms are in a low-to-moderate range (CES-D = 15, z = 0.18). These survey-derived features include several constructs (anxiety, depressive symptoms, stress, inconsistent sleep timing, alcohol use) that are positively associated with poorer subjective sleep in the study population and therefore increase the likelihood of sleep complaints even when objective sleep quantity appears adequate.

Balancing objective and subjective indicators, the dominant wearable-derived pattern suggests relatively preserved physiological sleep quality (sufficient duration, low fragmentation, structured circadian amplitude), which are typically associated with lower PSQI (better sleep). Countervailing evidence for worse PSQI comes from late and variable bedtimes, elevated trait anxiety and stress, and weekly alcohol use—factors that tend to drive worse subjective sleep quality and higher PSQI scores. Correlational signals in the dataset (notably CES-D and STAI correlations with PSQI) indicate that the participant’s elevated anxiety and modest depressive symptomatology are relevant risk markers for higher PSQI, but their effect must be weighed against objectively favorable sleep measures.

Overall assessment: the wearable and sleep-duration indicators provide stronger and multiple objective signals of consolidated sleep and regular circadian structure, while the self-report psychological and lifestyle factors introduce moderate risk for subjective sleep disturbance. On balance, the evidence favors placement in the lower half of the study’s PSQI distribution (i.e., relatively good/average sleep quality compared with peers), because objective sleep quantity and circadian regularity are overall supportive and the subjective risk factors are present but not extreme. Therefore the most likely grouping for this participant’s PSQI is bottom_50.

Psychological and behavioral profile: The participant reports modestly elevated depressive symptoms (CES-D = 16, Z = 0.28) and trait anxiety (STAI = 49, Z = 0.76). Reported stress is moderately above the sample mean (Z = 0.38), while momentary happiness and health-satisfaction are below average (happiness Z = -0.53; health satisfaction Z = -0.45). Self-esteem is relatively high (RSES = 39, Z = 0.11) and academic performance is strong (GPA in the mid-3.4–3.7 range). Social trust is lower than peers (Z = -1.42). Together, these data describe a profile with internalizing symptoms and elevated stressors that commonly correlate with poorer sleep, despite intact self-regard and academic functioning.

Behavioral sleep-related habits: Fitbit-derived sleep shows a median nightly sleep duration of 6 hours 41 minutes (Z = -0.61), indicating somewhat shorter sleep than the study average, with a nontrivial night-to-night variability in duration (SD ≈ 110 minutes, Z = 0.22). Typical sleep onset is late (median start ~00:39) with moderate variability in bedtimes (SD ≈ 67 minutes). Napping is minimal. Daily routines include moderate weekly alcohol use (beer and wine/liquor 1–2 times per week), low-to-moderate physical activity (exercise 1–2 times per week), and above-average time spent watching TV/videos. These habits (late bedtimes, shorter aggregated sleep, variable sleep duration, evening screen time and alcohol) are consistent with behavioral contributors to diminished perceived sleep quality in student samples.

Wearable physiological and circadian indicators: Circadian regularity metrics indicate modestly stable day-to-day structure (interdaily stability = 0.44, Z = 0.25) and low intraday fragmentation (intradaily variability = 0.37, Z = -1.24), which are features typically associated with more consolidated rest–activity rhythms. However, resting heart rate and mesor are substantially elevated relative to peers (resting HR = 78.2 bpm, mesor ≈ 91.4; both Z ≈ 2.38), while rhythm amplitude is slightly reduced (Z ≈ -0.5). Hourly aggregated heart rate deviations show the expected nocturnal drop (largest negative deviations ∼2–5 AM) and daytime elevations in the late morning and afternoon; the acrophase occurs in the mid-to-late afternoon (~4:05 PM). Elevated resting/midline heart rate combined with somewhat blunted amplitude can reflect increased physiological arousal or cardiorespiratory load despite a generally regular circadian pattern.

Integration and implications for sleep quality (PSQI): Several features point toward relatively poorer sleep quality: elevated depressive and anxiety symptoms (which correlate positively with PSQI in this sample, r ≈ 0.49 and 0.40 respectively), somewhat shorter median sleep duration and late sleep timing, and moderate night-to-night variability in sleep duration and onset (both correlated modestly with higher PSQI). Physiological data show elevated resting heart rate and mesor—small positive correlations with PSQI—suggesting greater baseline physiological arousal that can disrupt restorative sleep. Countervailing evidence includes low intradaily variability (indicating consolidated daily rhythm) and minimal napping, which are generally favorable for sleep. Overall, the weight of behavioral, affective, and physiological indicators—especially the moderate depressive/anxiety symptom burden combined with shorter, later, and somewhat variable sleep—aligns more closely with the pattern associated with higher PSQI scores in this population.

Conclusion (PSQI group): Considering the balance of evidence and the relative magnitudes of the associations with PSQI within the study sample, the participant is more likely to fall in the top half of the PSQI distribution (worse sleep quality) than the bottom half.

Psychological profile and self-reported affect: The participant reports a modestly elevated level of depressive symptoms (CES-D = 17, Z = 0.38) while reporting relatively low trait anxiety (STAI = 37, Z = -0.43) and above-average current happiness (self-rated 5.0, Z = 1.64). Self-esteem is relatively high (RSES = 35, Z = -0.45) and perceived health satisfaction is above the sample mean (5.33, Z = 0.8). Reported stress is near the sample average (22, Z = 0.1). These data indicate a mixed affective profile: there is evidence of elevated depressive symptoms that are potentially relevant to subjective sleep complaints (the CES-D score shows a moderate-to-strong positive correlation with PSQI, r ≈ 0.5), but other indicators (low trait anxiety, high happiness and self-esteem) suggest the participant is not broadly characterized by high chronic anxiety or global low well‑being.

Behavioral habits relevant to sleep: The participant engages in minimal alcohol or drug use but reports very low levels of physical activity (exercise frequency Z-scores roughly between -1.1 and -1.6) and elevated sedentary recreational screen time (video games 2–3 hours daily, Z = 3.23; other sedentary hobbies Z ≈ 2.0). Socializing and internet use are modestly above the mean. Low exercise and high evening screen-based recreation are behavioral patterns that commonly co-occur with later bedtimes and may influence subjective sleep quality and sleep latency, although their direct correlations with PSQI in this dataset are small-to-moderate.

Wearable-derived sleep and circadian physiology: Objective sleep metrics indicate generally favorable and regular sleep timing and duration. Median nightly sleep duration is approximately 7 hours 5 minutes (Z = -0.12), with low night-to-night variability (SD = 58 minutes, Z = -0.98). Napping is absent (mean daily naps = 0, Z = -0.86). The median sleep start time is late (about 01:14 AM) but consistent across nights (sleep start SD ≈ 55 minutes, Z = -0.61). Cardiovascular circadian markers show a coherent rhythm: interdaily stability is moderate-to-high (0.51, Z = 0.83), intradaily variability is modest (0.59, Z = 0.32), and autocorrelation at 24 hours is positive (0.41, Z = 0.73), indicating regular day-to-day structure in heart-rate patterns. Hourly aggregated heart-rate deviations show the expected substantial nocturnal decline (~-12 to -17 bpm across 2–6 AM) and an evening peak with higher than average deviations (notably 7–8 PM). Resting heart rate (60.7 bpm, Z = 0.3) and mean mesor (73.25, Z = -0.09) are near sample averages. Together these signals are consistent with physiologically consolidated sleep windows and intact circadian timing despite a late habitual bedtime.

Integration and interpretation for sleep quality (PSQI): Objective wearable data—adequate median sleep duration near seven hours, low night-to-night variability, lack of daytime napping, and coherent circadian structure—are most consistent with average-to-good sleep quantity and physiological consolidation of sleep. Against this, the participant’s late habitual sleep onset (≈1:15 AM) and elevated depressive symptom score (CES-D) are risk factors for poorer subjective sleep quality; CES-D shows a relatively strong positive correlation with PSQI in the sample, implying depressive symptom burden often accompanies worse self-reported sleep. Behavioral patterns of low physical activity and high evening screen time could also contribute to later bedtimes or subjective sleep complaints. Balancing the evidence, objective markers that directly index sleep duration, regularity, and nocturnal physiological dipping are reasonably favorable and the participant lacks marked physiological circadian disruption. The depressive symptom signal increases the likelihood of some subjective difficulties, but on net the multimodal profile leans toward overall sleep quality being in the lower half of the study’s PSQI distribution (i.e., better/average sleep rather than among the worst sleepers).

Psychological and behavioral profile: The participant reports low depressive symptom burden (CES-D = 8, Z = -0.55) and low perceived stress (Stress score Z = -2.34), while trait anxiety is modestly elevated relative to the sample (STAI = 44, Z = 0.27). Self-esteem and momentary happiness are slightly below sample means (RSES Z = -0.45; Happiness Z = -0.53). Health satisfaction is lower than average (Z = -1.11) and body mass index is in the overweight range (BMI = 28.7). Recreational substance use is minimal and group exercise occurs at a moderate frequency (1–2 times/week), but overall solitary exercise and sports participation are low. The participant has high daily internet use (>4 hours, Z = 2.19) and above-average time watching TV/videos (Z = 1.28), which indicate relatively elevated evening/at-home sedentary media exposure.

Circadian and physiological summary: Heart-rate–based circadian metrics indicate a well-structured, regular daily rhythm. Interdaily stability is relatively high (0.51, Z = 0.83) and the 24-hour autocorrelation is elevated (Z = 0.81), consistent with consistent timing of daily behaviors across days. Mesor and resting heart rate are higher than sample means (Mesor = 79.4, Z = 0.74; Resting HR = 64.8, Z = 0.79), while amplitude is near average. Hourly deviations from the mesor show the expected nocturnal trough (large negative deviations between ~12:00–7:00 AM) and daytime elevations peaking in the early afternoon, with an acrophase at ~4:00 PM. These patterns suggest intact day–night separation of physiological arousal and a stable circadian structure across the recording period.

Sleep timing and duration characteristics: Wearable-derived sleep metrics show a median sleep onset near 00:59 (≈1:00 AM) with moderate night-to-night variability in start time (SD ≈ 89 min, Z = 0.14) and total sleep duration of approximately 6 hours 51 minutes (Z = -0.42). Sleep duration variability (SD = 108 minutes, Z = 0.16) is slightly above average but not extreme, and mean daily naps were effectively absent (0, Z = -0.86). Taken together, the participant typically initiates sleep around midnight–1:00 AM, obtains just under 7 hours on median nights, and maintains generally consistent day-to-day timing, without compensatory napping.

Integration and likely impact on sleep quality (PSQI-relevant considerations): Several features predict relatively favorable global sleep quality: strong interdaily stability and a clear circadian rhythm (both associated with better sleep regularity), the absence of daytime naps, and low self-reported stress and depressive symptom burden. Contra-indicators are a habitual bedtime near 1:00 AM, modestly insufficient median sleep duration (slightly below 7 hours), elevated internet/media use (which can impair sleep onset or sleep quality), modest trait anxiety (which correlates with worse PSQI in the sample), and elevated resting HR / BMI (physiological factors that can relate to sleep complaints). Correlations provided with PSQI show moderate associations for depressive symptoms and anxiety (CES-D r ≈ 0.5; STAI r ≈ 0.4), but the participant’s CES-D is low and STAI only modestly elevated. Circadian stability metrics that tend to relate to better PSQI are relatively favorable for this individual (interdaily stability Z = 0.83).

Overall PSQI group assessment: Balancing the evidence, the participant shows more indicators consistent with average-to-better sleep quality (stable circadian rhythm, low stress and depressive symptoms, no naps) than with pronounced sleep disturbance. The modestly late sleep timing and slightly short median duration, plus elevated media use and some trait anxiety, could produce some PSQI component elevations but do not outweigh the favorable circadian regularity and low affective burden. On balance, the participant is more consistent with a PSQI score in the lower half of the study distribution (i.e., not among the worst sleepers).

Psychological and behavioral profile:
The participant reports low depressive symptom burden (CES-D = 6; Z = -0.76) and generally favorable well-being indicators: above-average self-reported happiness (Z = 0.55) and high satisfaction with physical health (Z = 0.55). Trait anxiety is modestly elevated relative to the sample (STAI = 44; Z = 0.27), a feature that typically relates to poorer subjective sleep in this cohort (STAI—PSQI correlation ≈ 0.40). The participant is physically active: frequent team/partner exercise and sports (both ~three times/week or more; Z-scores 1.23 and 1.58), minimal substance use, and no regular napping. Taken together, the survey profile indicates a mostly healthy lifestyle with some anxiety-proneness that could modestly influence sleep perception.

Objective sleep and self-report sleep behavior:
Wearable-recorded sleep shows robust nightly duration: median sleep duration is 8 hours 28 minutes (Z = 1.59), well above the study mean. Sleep timing centers near midnight (median start ≈ 00:03) with moderate night-to-night variability in start time (SD ≈ 82 minutes; Z ≈ -0.02) and sleep duration variability (SD ≈ 84 min; Z ≈ -0.38). The participant does not habitually nap (mean daily naps = 0; Z = -0.86). These objective metrics—long median sleep, few naps, and generally consistent timing—would usually be expected to correspond with relatively good sleep quantity and recovery.

Physiological circadian and heart-rate patterns:
Cardiac markers reflect a low-resting cardiovascular profile (resting HR = 51.4 bpm; Z = -0.80; mesor = 63.1; Z = -1.48), suggesting good baseline cardiovascular fitness or parasympathetic tone. Circadian summary features show reduced interdaily stability (0.35; Z ≈ -0.49) and elevated intradaily variability (0.69; Z ≈ 1.02). This combination indicates that, across days, the participant’s heart rate rhythm is somewhat irregular between days and shows relatively high within-day fragmentation—patterns that can be associated with inconsistent activity or sleep fragmentation even when total sleep time is long. Hourly aggregate deviations show expected nocturnal reductions in heart rate (~-10 to -17 bpm through the night) and daytime peaks in the afternoon/evening (notably an elevated 8–9 pm deviation, Z = 2.19), consistent with periods of higher evening arousal or activity for this individual.

Synthesis and implications for sleep quality:
Objective evidence points to abundant sleep opportunity and favorable recovery physiology (long median sleep, low resting HR, regular bedtime near midnight, no naps). Behavioral context—frequent exercise, low substance use, and good health satisfaction—also supports better sleep. Countervailing signals include modestly elevated trait anxiety and circadian rhythm indicators of inter-day irregularity and intra-day fragmentation (higher intradaily variability), which can degrade subjective sleep quality or produce non-restorative sleep despite long total sleep time. Correlations in the dataset suggest anxiety and rhythm irregularity are modest contributors to worse PSQI, but the participant’s strong objective sleep quantity, active lifestyle, and low depressive symptoms weigh more heavily toward relatively good sleep functioning in comparison to the study population.

Overall classification (PSQI distribution):
Balancing the multimodal evidence—particularly the high median sleep duration (Z = 1.59), absence of naps, low resting heart rate, frequent exercise, and generally positive self-reports—against the smaller adverse signals (moderate trait anxiety and elevated intradaily variability), the preponderance of evidence indicates this participant is more likely to fall in the lower half of the study PSQI distribution (i.e., better/average sleep quality rather than poorer sleep). Accordingly, the participant is classified as below the population median for PSQI (bottom 50%).

Body mass index is elevated (BMI = 28.7) and self-rated health satisfaction is lower than average (score = 3.22, Z = -0.78). In sum, the psychological and lifestyle profile shows some risk factors for poorer sleep (elevated trait anxiety, low exercise, higher BMI, lower health satisfaction) alongside protective factors (high self-esteem, low substance use, moderate happiness).

Wearable-derived circadian and cardiac physiology
Folded heart-rate features indicate a relatively strong and regular circadian rhythm. Parametric circadian measures are pronounced: mesor (mean level) is elevated relative to the study sample (82.2 bpm, Z = 1.13) and amplitude is substantially higher than peers (16.02 bpm, Z = 1.69), while acrophase is in the early evening (≈ 5:43 PM). Non-parametric rhythm metrics show above-average interdaily stability (0.48, Z = 0.58) and low intradaily variability (0.35, Z = -1.38), and autocorrelation at 24 hours is high (0.44, Z = 0.98). Together these indicate consistent day-to-day timing of activity/physiology and relatively low fragmentation of the circadian signal—features that are generally associated with better objective sleep consolidation. Resting heart rate is modestly low (56.9 bpm, Z = -0.15). Hourly aggregate deviations show a pronounced nocturnal heart-rate nadir (largest negative deviations of ~ -25 bpm between ~3–7 AM) and a prominent evening peak (largest positive deviation ~24.7 bpm at 7–8 PM, Z = 2.29), implying clear day–night separation in autonomic tone but also relatively elevated evening arousal.

Objective and self-reported sleep behavior
Wearable sleep metrics indicate a median nightly sleep duration of about 6 hours 49 minutes (Z = -0.46), placing the participant below the study median for duration but not extremely so. Night-to-night variability in sleep duration is relatively high (SD ≈ 151 minutes, Z = 1.14), indicating inconsistent total sleep time across nights; sleep start time is late on average (median ≈ 01:28 AM) with a moderate spread (start SD ≈ 80 minutes, Z ≈ -0.06). Napping is rare. These sleep timing and variability features are relevant because later sleep onset and greater variability in sleep duration are both correlated with higher PSQI scores in this dataset (sleep variability r ≈ 0.20; timing variability r ≈ 0.18). At the same time, the low intradaily variability and high interdaily stability from the wearable data argue for a relatively structured daily rhythm, which can mitigate some consequences of late timing.

Integrative interpretation regarding sleep quality (PSQI)
Evidence for poorer sleep quality: the participant has a late habitual sleep onset (~1:28 AM), a median nightly duration below 7 hours, and elevated night-to-night variability in sleep length; trait anxiety is above average and correlates positively with PSQI in this sample. These features (late timing, short median duration, high variability, and higher anxiety) are each associated with higher PSQI scores and could contribute to greater subjective sleep disturbance. Evidence for comparatively better sleep: robust circadian structure (high interdaily stability, low intradaily fragmentation, high 24-hour autocorrelation), low resting heart rate, minimal naps, and limited substance use are all indicators that favor objectively consolidated sleep and lower disturbance. Balancing these data, the most salient risks for poorer PSQI in this participant are the late bedtimes and the sizable night-to-night variability combined with elevated trait anxiety and low physical activity. The circadian regularity appears to moderate risk but does not fully offset the impact of late timing and inconsistent sleep duration, both of which tend to influence the components of the PSQI (latency, duration, efficiency, disturbances). Therefore, when integrating self-report and wearable signals with their known associations to PSQI in this sample, the overall pattern is more consistent with a PSQI score in the higher half of the study distribution.
